Mitosis and  Cytokinesis 	  During mitosis, when the nucleus divides, the two chromatids that make up each chromosome separate from each other and move to opposite poles of the cell. This is shown in Figure 2.60. You can watch an animation of the process at the following link: URL . Mitosis actually occurs in four phases. The phases are called prophase, metaphase, anaphase, and telophase. They are shown in Figure 2.61 and described in greater detail in the following sections. 
